Because you want to have deterministic unit tests. Using randomness may trigger going through different code paths each time the test is run, changing the coverage and creating toggling results.

If you want to test a few combinations of values, you can do that with parameterized tests. The advantage over rand() is that they are deterministic and you can check a few sets of values in one run of the test suite.

You can read about it here - https://github.com/google/googletest/blob/master/googletest/docs/AdvancedGuide.md#value-parameterized-tests
It is not a good idea to use rand() here.

I can see precondition and postcondition in the title, but not the trigger. Also, it seems there is only postcondition check in the test body, but actually that function does more than that.
IMHO that function should be removed and its content moved into this test.

I feel like inheriting from TestStrategy enforces too rigid structure and hides the implementation of tests in spread out functions. The body of the test should be visible where the test is defined.

As for the title, the data in UTs is always fake or irrelevant, because we're testing logic, so "GivenFakeDataConfig" can be omitted. I don't like "CheckConfigIsSet", because it's too generic and doesn't really state what is the expected result. Moreover, the config is not simply copied from one structure to another, there are calculations in the middle of it. So the title should state that calculations are performed correctly.

A simpler title could be "configureShouldCalculateAndStoreTaParameters".
I didn't use words given/when/then, because they're only one of ways to convey preconditions, trigger and postconditions. I chose "trigger should do something" template. You can use anything as long as it's clear to the reader.

If you think that my postcondition is also too generic, you can split this test into many smaller, where each test case checks one calculation at a time. That's also another reason to get rid of TestStrategy base class.

No, to me TODO comments are equally bad. You shouldn't write tests that do nothing, because it means you don't know what you are expecting from the behavior of the implementation.

Using max() to get expected value seems strange, as if you didn't know what the expected value should be ;-). It should be removed together with usages of rand().

Right now you check if a calculation algorithm is equal to that same calculation algorithm. It will always be true. If there is a bug in the calculation, it will not be caught, because both versions are the same.

What you should do is give the result directly or arrive at the result through differently written algorithm.

It's like testing a function int sum(int a, int b). You can test it with EXPECT_EQ(5, sum(2, 3)). Going back to your example, you can also write expectedTaOffScheMarg = testConfigData.taOffScheMarg * factor, where you would have to calculate yourself the value of factor to get the same result as with bitshift and division.

The biggest problem I see is that you first written implementation and then you are writing tests for it instead of the other way around. In Test Driven Development you first write a test, which fails, because there is no implementation. But you know what you want to achieve as the result for given inputs. Then you write minimal implementation to pass the test. Once it's done, you refactor the implementation and repeat the cycle. In short it's called "red, green, refactor". You can read more about this here - https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_driven_development

Every code branch should be tested in UTs. Then above that you can choose what levels of testing you want to use for specific parts of code.

I know the ship has sailed for the current class, but you can try to use TDD methodology to design next classes and functions.

please use triangle brackets for includes. it makes it so much easier to understand project structure.

with triangle brackets you have to state relative path to file. So it is easier to understand dependencies between modules and spot unwanted rederences (i.e. including files from old file structure in new one. including scheduler code from prescheduler, ul-code from dl, etc).

with quote-includes, on the other hand, it is impossible to say if included file is in the same folder, in old file structure, in the ISAR folders, or god knows where.

Pavlo, can you please explain why it should be explicit constructor ?

consider having function 

void doSomething(const TimeAlignmentStrategyLegacy& param);

now it is possible to call it like this

doSomething(0);

which is in most cases not what the author wanted, because 0 is clearly not the valid Time Alignment Strategy

But it will still compile and run, because 0 is a constant used for the null-pointer in C++. and TimeAlignmentStrategyLegacy object will be constructed in place 

moreover, if someone will add method doSomething(u32 param); than the above code will silently change it's meaning and will start calling new method.

to avoid all this mess it is easier to mark constructor as explicit to prevent all the unexpected and unwanted implicit casting. it is especially true when constructor accepts pointer parameter

If you want to differentiate different parts of test, you can start functions with:
- setUp/configure/expect/given for preconditions
- nothing/when for triggers
- check/assert/then for postconditions

Of course you can use different prefixes as long as it's clear what is happening in the test.

* it is preferred to use EXPECT_ macros, unless you actually need to stop test if the condition is false
* *_EQ macro accepts expected value as a first parameter and actual as a second. it seems that you have wrong order here

You can usually just use constructor and destructor instead of SetUp() and TearDown(). Usually you can even not declare the destructor at all (the compiler will generate virtual destructor automatically, because ::testing::Test has a virtual destructor).

You should use SetUp() when you want to use virtual functions of the test suite class when building the test suite, which sounds like a rare case.
You should use TearDown() when destroying the test suite can throw an exception, which also should not happen in most cases.

I would not do parametrised test for testing shortCycle.

if (drxParams.drxShortCycle <= 0 || (drxParams.drxLongCycle % drxParams.drxShortCycle) != 0 || drxParams.drxShortCycle < drxParams.drxOnDuratT)

I would do:
1) tests for "drxParams.drxShortCycle <= 0" - so test drxShortCycle=0
2) test relation: drxParams.drxLongCycle % drxParams.drxShortCycle) != 0
3) test relation: drxParams.drxShortCycle < drxParams.drxOnDuratT (if possible, because I remember you told me sthg was impossible to test, I am not sure what)

The conditions for shortCycle (except 1) are in fact conditions for relations (with other parameter), so you should not set hardcoded invalid values, because they may be valid in some cases (when other parameters have matching values).
